stablished to fill this gap: since its inception it has been providing banking services to poor, illiterate self-employed women and has become a viable financial venture. SEWA provides a range of banking and other social services to its members in both urban and rural areas. For more information go to: www.sewabank.com PlEAsE ConTInuE To THE nExT PAGE >> Women and HIV in the Asia-Pacific Region - A Development Practitioner\u2019s Guide 124 REsouRCEs Economy and Epidemic. Microfinance and HIV/ AIDS in Asia. Stuart Mathison. The Foundation for Development Cooperation. 2004 HIV/AIDS and work: Global estimates, impact and response. The ILO Programme on HIV/AIDS and the World of Work HIV/AIDS, Health, Safety, and the Youth Employment Summit: A Call to Action. Education Development Center, Inc. A Sectoral Breakout Session Paper for the Youth Employment Summit 2002 http://www.yesweb.org/gkr/res/ bg.hivaids.bo.doc Urdang S. 2007. Change, Choice and Power: young women, livelihoods and HIV prevention. Literature Review and Case Study Analysis. IPPF/ UNFPA/Young Positives. Available at: http://www. unfpa.org/upload/lib_pub_file/674_filename_ change.pdf REFEREnCEs Blanc, A. (2001). The effect of power in Sexual Re- lationships on Reproductive and Sexual Health: An examination of the Evidence - prepared for the Population Council Meeting on power in Sexual Relationships. BRIDGE, IDS at http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/re- ports/BB15Masculinities.pdf Drimie, S. (2002b). \u201cThe Impact of HIV/AIDS on Rural Households and Land Issues in Southern and Eastern Africa.\u201d Background Paper prepared for the FAO Sub-regional Office for Southern and Eastern Africa. Pretoria: Human Sciences Re- search Council. Drimie, S. 2002. The Impact of HIV/AIDS on Ru- ral Households and Land Issues in Southern and Eastern Africa. Rome, Italy: Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) Sub- Regional Office for Southern and Eastern Africa. Dunkle, Kristin L et al. 2004. \u201dGender-ba