People with AIDS have the right: 1. To as full and satisfying sexual and emotional lives as anyone else\u2019s. 2. To quality medical treatment and quality social service provision without discrimination of any form based on sexual orientation, gender, diagnosis, economic status, or race. 3. To full explanations of all medical procedures and risks, to choose or refuse their treatment modalities, to refuse to participate in research without jeopardizing their treatment, and to make informed decisions about their lives. 4. To privacy, confidentiality of medical records, to human respect, and to choose who their significant others are. 5. To die and to LIVE in dignity. 1* HIV and the first proof that AIDS was an infectious disease was only discovered in 1985 2* In 1983 it had not yet been scientifically proven that condoms effectively protect against HIV transmission 5 The Denver Principles A GUIDANCE NOTE FOR DEVELOPMENT PRACTITIONERS 53 Below is a selection of useful and relevant documents for further reading that relate to the involvement and empowerment of people living with HIV/AIDS: APN+ Position Paper. 2004. Asia-Pacific Network of People Living with HIV and AIDS (APN+). http://www.gnpplus.net/cms-downloads/files/APN_GIPA_position.doc AIDS Discrimination in Asia. 2004: APN+. APN+ Strategic Plan Document 2006-2010. 2006: APN+. From Involvement to Empowerment. 2004: UNDP RCC. http://www.undprcc.lk/Publications/Publications/frominvtoemp.pdf. Law, Ethics and HIV/AIDS in South Asia. 2002: UNDP RCC http://www.undprcc.lk/Publications/Publications/LawEthicsandHIVAIDS.pdf. Quiet Storm: Celebrating the Triumph of Human Spirit over HIV/AIDS. 2004: UNDP and Penguin Enterprise. Positive Development Manual (GPN+ document). Positive Development. 1998: GPN+. Lifting the Burden of Secrecy \u2013 A Manual for HIV-Positive People Who Want to Speak Out in Public. 1999: APN+. www.hivasiapacifc.apdip.net \u2018Valued Voices\u2019, GIPA Toolkit: A Manual for the Greater Involvement of